{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516367","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516367"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:41:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:41:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12611"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12611","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12611"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.7,0.1,0.02,0.02,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5098"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80607"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5098"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12611"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65898"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2765"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8528"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12197"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14280"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27513"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42787"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80607"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-hour history of central chest heaviness, shortness of breath, and vomiting. He has a medical history of hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia. His medications include perindopril and atorvastatin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears short of breath. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 95% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. There is no radio-radial delay or radio-femoral delay, and blood pressures are equal in both arms. The jugular venous pressure is elevated, and there is mild pitting oedema in the lower limbs. His chest is clear on auscultation. Chest X-ray shows clear lung fields. His electrocardiogram shows 2 mm ST depression in leads V2-V3 with no ST elevation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter administration of glyceryl trinitrate for pain relief, his blood pressure decreases to 85/70 mmHg but recovers to 100/60 mmHg following a 500 mL bolus of 0.9% saline. The chest pain improves with glyceryl trinitrate.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Posterior infarction with right ventricular failure","Pulmonary embolism with right heart failure","Pericarditis with left heart failure","Aortic dissection","Anterior infarction with left ventricular failure"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis is \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior infarction with right ventricular failure\u003C/strong\u003E. ST depression in the anterior leads (V1-V3) is common with posterior myocardial infarction. The elevated jugular venous pressure, clear lung fields, and hypotension responsive to fluid are classic features of right ventricular involvement. Right ventricular infarction typically occurs with occlusion of the right coronary or circumflex artery. The hypotension after glyceryl trinitrate administration, which improves with fluid, is characteristic as the right ventricle is preload dependent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary embolism with right heart failure\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with sudden onset dyspnoea, pleuritic chest pain, and hypoxia. While it can cause right heart strain, the ECG typically shows sinus tachycardia, right bundle branch block, or right axis deviation rather than ST depression. The normal oxygen saturation and improvement with glyceryl trinitrate make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPericarditis with left heart failure\u003C/strong\u003E requires at least two of: pericarditic chest pain, pericardial rub, pericardial effusion, or characteristic ECG changes (diffuse ST elevation or PR depression). The acute presentation and absence of these features make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAortic dissection\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with tearing chest pain radiating to the back, which is not relieved by glyceryl trinitrate. Blood pressure differentials between arms or radio-radial delay would be expected, which are absent here. Hypotension in dissection is typically not fluid responsive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior infarction with left ventricular failure\u003C/strong\u003E would show ST elevation (not depression) in V1-V3. Left ventricular failure typically causes pulmonary oedema with crackles on auscultation and infiltrates on chest X-ray, which are absent here.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["ST depression in anterior leads V1-V3 is common with posterior myocardial infarction.","Right ventricular infarction presents with elevated JVP, clear lung fields, and hypotension that is responsive to fluid.","Glyceryl trinitrate should be used cautiously in right ventricular infarction as it can cause profound hypotension."],"references":["Fardman A, Charron P, Imazio M, Adler Y. European Guidelines on Pericardial Diseases: a Focused Review of Novel Aspects. Curr Cardiol Rep. 2016 May;18(5):46. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27007597/","Byrne RA, Rossello X, Coughlan JJ, Barbato E, Berry C, Chieffo A, et al; ESC Scientific Document Group. 2023 ESC Guidelines for the management of acute coronary syndromes. Eur Heart J. 2023 Oct 12;44(38):3720-3826. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37622654/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65898"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12611"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65898"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-21T20:41:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-21T20:41:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5098"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80607"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"